column12: MAGAZINE LATCHING ASSEMBLY FOR A COMPACT TACKER
column13: A compact tacker for driving fasteners into a workpiece includes a housing defining a handle and a nose portion. A driver is reciprocally mounted within a drive track defined within the nose portion. The tacker also includes a magazine assembly slideably mounted within the housing including a forward end that is positioned adjacent the drive track such that the driver reciprocates between the nose and the forward end of the magazine assembly. A bistable biasing member is mounted within the housing and in a first stable position, biases the magazine toward the nose and in a second stable position biases the magazine assembly away from the nose. In the second position there is defined an open area around the drive track to allow removal of jammed fasteners.
column15: FRANK EDMUND

column12: Apparatus for handling flexible containers for liquid sample spectrometry
column13: Flexible sample containers for liquid scintillation spectrometry analysis of test samples containing one or more radioactive isotopes disposed in a liquid scintillator wherein the flexible sample containers either in individual or strip form are made of layered, flexible, light-transmissive, polyester film and are provided further with means for avoiding light "piping" or optical isolation from respective adjacent sample containers. Apparatus for handling such flexible sample containers is provided with light transmission sealing means for preventing entry of ambient light or escape of light from the photomultiplier tube detection devices. Also disclosed are methods and apparatus for filling, forming, sealing and handling the aforementioned flexible sample containers that readily lends itself to fully automated production line type operations.
column15: FRANK EDMUND

column12: Elevator mechanism and method for scintillation detectors
column13: An elevator mechanism and method for raising and lowering radioactive samples through a shielded vertical counting chamber in a benchtop scintillation detector which has a practical limit on its height. The elevator mechanism adds little or nothing to the height of the detector by using an elongated flexible member such as a metal tape secured to the bottom of the elevator platform and extending downwardly through the counting chamber and its bottom shielding, where the tape is bent laterally for connection to a drive means. In the particular embodiment illustrated, the tape is bent laterally below the bottom shielding for the counting chamber, and then upwardly along or through one side of the shielding to a reel at the top of the shielding. The tape is wound onto the reel, and the reel is driven by a reversible motor which winds and unwinds the tape on the reel to raise and lower the elevator platform.
column15: FRANK EDMUND

column12: Improvements relating to vacuum stop valves
column13: 743,537. Valves. METROPOLITANVICKERS ELECTRICAL CO., Ltd. April 5, 1954 [April 10, 1953], No. 9851/53. Class 135. A vacuum stop valve mounted e.g. on a vapour condensation or diffusion pump, comprises a cylindrical housing 1, Fig. 2, having flanges 2, 3 sealingly connected to the pump and the vacuum system respectively and a valve plate 8 biased away from its seating 21 by springs 11 abutting brackets 10 and slidably mounted on guide rods 6 equally spaced around the housing. A crank arm 16 rotated anticlockwise from a horizontal position either manually or mechanically on rotation of a shaft 12 brings a roller 18 progressively into engagement with the valve plate to close the valve. column12: Sensor for monitoring the immediate vicinity of a motor vehicle
column13: A sensor for monitoring the immediate vicinity of a motor vehicle comprises an infrared emitter that is arranged behind a lens and a receiver for reflected infrared radiation, as well as an evaluation unit for detecting the presence of an object in the immediate vicinity of the motor vehicle, wherein a signal can be forwarded from the evaluation unit to a control device in the motor vehicle. In order to also ensure the proper function of the sensor when the lens is soiled, an infrared emitter and a receiver are provided for measuring the transparency of the lens, wherein the evaluation unit is able to increase the power of the infrared emitter for monitoring the immediate vicinity of the motor vehicle if it determines that the lens transparency is reduced.

column12: Regulation of prechamber airflow for internal combustion engine
column13: The invention relates to an arrangement for a pre-combustion chamber of an internal combustion engine and a pre-combustion chamber comprising such an arrangement, in particular to regulating or adjusting a gas flow in a gas purged pre-combustion chamber prior to entering a combustion zone. Thus, an arrangement (10) for a pre-chamber gas valve of an internal combustion engine is proposed, comprising a housing (14) having an outer surface (16) and comprising a channel (18), a first end (20) of the channel (18) being in fluid communication with the outer surface (16), a second end (22) of the channel (18) being connectable to a valve seat of the pre-chamber gas valve; and at least one protrusion (34) extending from an outer surface (16) of the housing (14). The first end (20) of the passage (18) is arranged upstream of the second end (22) of the passage (18) and downstream of the at least one protrusion (34), wherein the arrangement (10) is configured to absorb heat from a combustion portion of the internal combustion engine arranged downstream of the second end (22) and to regulate the gas upstream of the second end (22) using only the heat when the arrangement (10) is in an installed condition.

column12: TRACKER FALSE ALARM RATE CONTROL
column13: The present invention relates to a method of reducing false alarms. Specifically, the present invention relates to reducing the number of false alarms reported as tracks by a radar tracker. The present invention provides a method of reducing false alarms issued by a radar installation, the method comprising the steps of; establishing a map corresponding to a surveillance area; populating the map with plots derived from plot data returned from the radar installation over a number of looks; identifying an apparent target; generating one or more cells in the map dependent on the location of the plot data contained in the map and a channel occupied by the apparent target; calculating a clutter density associated with the, or each, cell; and determining a status of the apparent target dependent on the, or each, clutter density. This method of reducing false alarms in the detection of targets is, therefore, able to optimise the computational burden the system dedicates to computing an accurate clutter estimate.

column12: High pressure hydraulic testing packer
column13: A resilient packer that may be mounted on a high pressure hydraulic testing unit to permit the unit to be moved axially through a string of tubular members connected end to end by collars. The tubular members have flat ring-shaped end surfaces that are disposed as pairs within the collars connecting the tubular members. The end surfaces of each of the pairs are longitudinally spaced a substantial distance. The packer is of such structure that a portion thereof is radially compressed into fluid sealing contact with the interior surface of the tubular member in which it is disposed, but which packer will not hang up on one of the end surfaces when it traverses the longitudinal space between a pair thereof as the testing unit is axially moved through the string of tubular members.

column12: Polyurethane prepolymers, methods of producing polyurethane foams therefrom, and the foams thus produced
column13: A non-linear polyurethane prepolymer adapted for formation of polyurethane foam comprises the reaction product of a non-linear hydroxyl-terminated polyether, formed by condensing an alkylene oxide with a trihydric alcohol and having a molecular weight within the range from 1200 to 6400, and an organic diisocyanate present in an amount exceeding that required for reaction with the hydroxyl-terminated polyether and such as will give rise to foam formation upon addition of water. As the trihydric alcohols there are spefified glycerol, hexanetriol -1,2,6, 2,2- dihydroxy-methyl -1- butanol, 2,2-dihydroxy-ethyl butanol and the triol of the formula HOCH2 CH2OCH2C (CH3) (CH2OH) CH2CH-(CH3) CH2OH. The prepolymer may also contain an anti-oxidant, such as 2,6- ditbutyl -4- methylphenol and an antifoam agent such as a siloxane of the formula (CH3)3Si[OSi(CH3)2]n OSi-(CH3)3 where n is an integer from 0 to 2000. Dyestuffs, pigments, sulphur or sulphur-containing materials can be incorporated. Reference is also made to using phosgene and diprimary amines or biscarbamyl chlorides in place of diisocyanates in preparing the prepolymers. The prepolymer is converted to a foam by reaction with a material having ionizable hydroxyl groups, such as water or succinic acid, suitably in the presence of an accelerator such as methylpiperidine, tribenzylamine or pyridine. In examples prepolymers are prepared by reacting (1) glycerol/propylene oxide reaction product (M.W. 4000), and toluene diisocyanate in the presence of 2,6- di-t-butyl-4-methyl phenol; (2) glycerol/propylene oxide reaction product (M.W. 3000) successively with 3,31-bitolylene -4,4-1 diisocyanate and toluene diisocyanate. Conversion to foam products is effected by adding a mixture of water, N-methylmorpholine and triethylamine.

column12: Reducing copper corrosiveness of organic sulfides.
column13: Reducing the copper corrosiveness of organic sulfides by treating them with an alkali metal-containing or alkaline earth metal-containing substance capable of dissolving elemental sulfur (e.g., sodium hydroxide, sodium sulfide, etc.). The process is conducted in a substantially homogeneous liquid reaction medium composed of a mixture of water and at least one ketone. Experiments have shown that it is possible by use of this process to reduce the copper corrosiveness to a level below that exhibited by a product formed by treating the same initial organic sulfide in the same way but in a liquid medium composed solely of water.

column12: Improvements relating to spark igniters for gas appliances
column13: The present specification discloses a spark igniter for use in a gas appliance. The assembly comprises a piezo electric device (9) mounted on a control spindle (5) of a gas control valve (1). The piezo electric device (9) is designed to grip the control spindle (5) solely in one direction of relative rotation corresponding to movement of the control spindle (5) to open the valve (1). From the valve fully closed position, the piezo electric device (9) is free to rotate with the control spindle (5) for part of the available spindle rotation, said device (9) engaging a stop (15) for the remainder of the available spindle rotation. During the remainder of this available spindle rotation, the control spindle primes the piezo electric device so that it fires shortly before the limit of said available spindle rotation is reached. Return rotation of the control spindle does not affect the piezo electric device (9) and the piezo electric device can only be fired after the control spindle has first been returned to the valve fully closed position. <IMAGE>

A spring loaded contact 4 abuts against a portion of the electrode 3 outside the inner tube 1 and is arranged inside an insulating member 20 having a skirt portion screwed into the end of the tube 2 and housing a plug and socket connecter 19 to a high tension conductor. In the construction shown in Fig. 3 of the drawings accompanying the Provisional Specification the insulating member 20, preferably made of moulded plastic material, is rotatably secured to the tube 2, which may be made of metal, by spinning over the tube 2 at 21 so that the lead 6 can enter in a desired direction. The member 20 and tube 2 may be made integrally of moulded plastic material. In the construction shown in Figs. 1 (Prov.) and 2 the spring loaded contact 4 is arranged inside a closed end of the outer tube 2 and is connected to a terminal element 5 surrounded by a rubber protective cover 7 having a sleeve 14 accommodating the voltage supply conductor, 6, 6<SP>1</SP>, Fig. 1 (Prov.): or is connected to a button contact 15 engaged by a spring clip connector 16 connected through a soldering joint 17 to the supply conductor 6, 6<SP>1</SP>. column13: Reducing the copper corrosiveness of dihydrocarbyl polysulfides by treating them with an alkali metal-containing or alkaline earth metal-containing substance capable of dissolving elemental sulfur (e.g., sodium hydroxide or sodium sulfide). The process is conducted in a liquid reaction medium composed of a mixture of water and at least one water-soluble alcohol. Experiments have shown that it is possible by use of this process to reduce the copper corrosiveness to a level below that exhibited by a product formed by treating the same initial dihydrocarbyl polysulfide in the same way but in a liquid medium composed solely of water.

column12: Process for producing a sintered body
column13: A process is described for producing a sintered body which essentially consists of silicon nitride, by shaping a granular material or a powder essentially consisting of silicon and/or silicon nitride, which additionally contains oxides and/or hydroxides of aluminium, magnesium, calcium, the rare earths and/or yttrium, to give a green shaped body and sintering at temperatures of about 1700@C until a dense shaped body is formed. In the process, a suspension comprising an aqueous solution of at least one water-soluble salt of aluminium, magnesium, calcium, rare earths and/or yttrium and finely divided solid silicon and/or silicon nitride is treated with a base. The resulting solid phase containing the added solid and the precipitated hydroxide of aluminium, magnesium, calcium, rare earths and/or yttrium is isolated, dried and then the hydroxide content is converted at least partially into the free oxide or mixed oxide by heating, the granular material or powder being formed.

column12: Horizontal wrapper with a side seal attachment
column13: A continuously operating machine is provided for wrapping articles with a heat shrinkable plastic film automatically and sequentially. Articles are continuously, transferred along a horizontal pathway to a plurality of processing stations. At a first station, articles are tubularly overwrapped and sealed along a side edge thereof with excess film material being automatically trimmed away. Next, the articles are separated one from the other at a second station and at a last succeeding station, the resulting wrapped articles are subjected to thermal film shrinking. The side seal and trim apparatus includes a heat seal and trim unit which engages free side edges of the film tube to one another and trims excess away, the unit being sandwiched between drive and alignment members.

column12: SWITCHES FOR USE WITH ELECTRICAL STARTER MOTORS, FOR INTERNAL COMBUSTION ENGINES
column13: 1,202,713. Electromagnetic switches. JOSEPH LUCAS (INDUSTRIES) Ltd. 9 Feb., 1968 [14 Feb., 1967], No. 7004/67. Heading H1N. A switch for use with the starter motor of an internal-combustion engine has three fixed contacts, the first and second of which are engaged before the first and third are bridged by a resiliently urged contact bridge on an axially movable control rod. Energization of a solenoid not shown, moves two armatures 32, 33 toward a polepiece 13 which forms part of a contact casing 11. The contact bridge 21, which is spring urged against an angled face 18a of an insulator 18 on the rod 15 is first brought into engagement with fixed contacts 24, 25 and then pivots about these contacts until it also engages contact 26. Contacts 24, 25 are in the "low torque" circuit. of the starter motor and contacts 24, 26 in the "high torque" circuit of the motor. A pin 15a on the rod 15 extends in a slot 14a in a sleeve 14 and the backing spring 22 for the contact bridge 21 acts between washers 22a, 23 (the latter being insulating) against the bridge 21 and sleeve 14. The part 33 is coupled to a pinion (not shown) which when the part is moved on solenoid energization engages a toothed wheel to couple the starter motor to the engine. If tooth to tooth engagement occurs the rod 15 is not moved by the part 33 but the part 32 engages the end of the sleeve 14 to close only contacts 24, 25 so that the engine is driven at "low torque" until the teeth engage and part 33 moves to drive the rod 15 and complete the contact movement.

column12: Improvements in Clutches applicable for Motors or Engines of Motor Cycles, Motor Cars, Cranes and for other Purposes.
column13: 22,979. Isaacs, C. H., and Box, E. F. Oct. 23. Motor cycles; clutches. - Relates to clutches for the engine shafts of motor cycles &c. A driving - pulley a, or sprocket-wheel, is mounted loosely on the shaft h, but is prevented from moving longitudinally thereon by means of set-screws d engaging a groove in the shaft; or balls may be arranged to engage grooves in the shaft and in the pulley. The pulley is formed with a conical clutch face e adapted to engage a clutch member f provided with a face of leather, fibre, &c. The member f is mounted on the shaft b so as to be capable of sliding but not of turning, and is pressed into engagement by means of a spring. This spring h may be secured in a recess in the shaft and attached to a screw eye &c. k passing through a collar l, adapted to press against a washer on the clutch ; or a spring, in compression, may be arranged around the shaft b. The clutch members are disengaged by means of a lever n, which engages behind the washer on the clutch and is actuated by a wire or cord ; a ball bearing is interposed between the lever n and the washer. A collar or washer s on the end of the shaft prevents the clutch from coming off the shaft should the spring break.

column12: Improvements relating to mass spectrometer ion sources
column13: 948,957. Ion sources. ASSOCIATED ELECTRICAL INDUSTRIES Ltd. Oct. 8, 1962 [Oct. 13, 1961], No. 36863/61. Heading H1D. The evacuable chamber of a mass spectrometer ion source is provided with a transparent viewing aperture protected by a movable shutter which prevents the obscuring of the aperture by contaminating material emitted by the sample being ionized. As shown, an ion source comprises a chamber 1 having a transparent cover plate 3, insulating supports 5 which project inwardly through the cylindrical side wall 2 of the chamber for holding rods 6 of the sample material, mechanisms 8 for moving the supports 5, a shield 11 having an aperture 12 through which the rods 6 may be inspected, and a shutter 13, e.g. of tantalum, movable by a mechanism 16 so that it can be located between the aperture 12 and the cover 3 to prevent contamination of the latter when the sample material is ionized by producing a spark between the electrodes 6. The mechanism 16 includes a cam 24 mounted on a shaft 23 and attached to a bar 14 carrying the shutter 13, so that rotation of a hand wheel 25 moves the bar 14 into and out from the chamber 1. A mechanism including a magnet for moving the shutter 13 may replace the mechanism 16. In another embodiment, Figs. 2 and 3 (not shown), the shutter is pivoted within the chamber 1 and can be rotated into its protecting position.

column12: Improvements in or relating to streptomycin salts
column13: The invention relates to a salt of streptomycin and a phosphorylated inositol, especially one containing three molecules of streptomycin per molecule of phytic acid. The salt may be hydrated or anhydrous. Where free acid groups are available for further salt formation, non-toxic metal ions such as sodium, potassium, ammonium, calcium and magnesium may be present. The phytic acid (inositol hexaphosphoric acid) may be replaced by other inositol phosphoric acids such as the tri- and tetraphosphoric acid. It is preferred to react a water-soluble phytate, e.g. sodium phytate, with a water-soluble salt of streptomycin, e.g. streptomycin sulphate, in aqueous solution at a pH of 7 to 8, preferably after a preliminary treatment with carbon. Streptomycin phytate is therapeutically active, non-toxic and relatively insoluble in water. It is used medicinally (see Group VI) and in the recovery of streptomycin from aqueous solution.ALSO:A therapeutic preparation in the form of a powder, tablet, capsule or aqueous or oily suspension for oral or parenteral use, comprises a salt of streptomycin and a phosphorylated inositol, e.g. streptomycin phytate (see Group IV (b)) with or without the addition of other medicaments. An edible oil such as coconut oil or an injectable oil such as peanut oil, as such or gelled with aluminium monostearate, forms the vehicle for the oily suspensions. Optional ingredients are (a) suspending agents such as sodium carboxymethyl cellulose, methyl cellulose, polyvinyl alcohol, polyvinyl pyrrolidone, gum tragacanth, gelatine, pectin, alginates, dextrans, gum karaya, lecithin, polyoxyalkylene derivatives, glyceryl monostearate, inositol phosphoric acids and their non-toxic salts; (b) buffers such as sodium citrate or sodium phosphate; (c) preservatives, e.g. phenol, cresol, alkyl esters of p-hydroxy benzoic acid; (d) other pharmaceutical adjuvants. The particle size of the streptomycin phylate may be varied. Specified other medicaments are anti-histamines, sulpha drugs, vitamins, lipotropic agents, stimulants, analgesics, laxatives, sedatives and antibiotics such as potassium benzyl penicillin. The streptomycin phylate particles may be coated with a suspending agent such as lecithin.

column12: Spark igniters for gas appliances
column13: The igniter comprises a piezo electric device (1) mounted on a control spindle (13) of a gas control valve (15), the control spindle (13) being rotatable in both directions between limit positions and being in frictional engagement with a lobed cam (7). The piezo electric device (1) is fixed, and is actuated by the cam. When the control spindle is rotated in one sense to open the valve (15), either of the lobes (9) of the cam (7) can then lift and release a spring loaded hammer (17) to fire the piezo electric device (1) shortly before the rotational limit of the spindle (13) is reached. The available rotation of the control spindle (13) between said limit positions is preferably approximately 200 DEG and the piezo electric device (1) can only be primed and fired after the control spindle (13) has first been moved to a fully-off position and then moved in said one direction to approach the fully-on limit position.

column12: Neural regeneration peptides and methods for their use in treatment of brain damage
column13: The invention discloses a family of peptides termed NRP compounds or NRPs that can promote neuronal migration, neurite outgrowth, neuronal proliferation, neural differentiation and/or neuronal survival, and provides compositions and methods for the use of NRPs in the treatment of brain injury and neurodegenerative disease. NRP compounds can induce neurons and neuroblasts to proliferate and migrate into areas of damage caused by acute brain injury or chronic neurodegenerative disease, such as exposure to toxins, stroke, trauma, nervous system infections, demyelinating diseases, dementias, and metabolic disorders. NRP compounds may be administered directly to a subject or to a subject's cells by a variety of means including orally, intraperitoneally, intravascularly, and directly into the nervous system of a patient. NRP compounds can be formulated into pharmaceutically acceptable dose forms for therapeutic use. Methods for detecting neural regeneration, neural proliferation, neural differentiation, neurite outgrowth and neural survival can be used to develop other neurally active agents.

column12: SYSTEMS AND METHODS FOR GENERATING SMART CONTRACTS TO MANAGE ESCROW TRANSACTIONS
column13: The present disclosure relates to systems and methods for configuring, creating, and deploying smart contracts to facilitate managing and execution of escrow transactions. Embodiments provide for receiving information about an escrow transaction that includes at least one term required to be met for digital property, provided by a funding party, to be distributed to a performing party. Embodiments also include generating a transaction smart contract based on the transaction information. The transaction smart contract is configured to hold the digital property until a triggering event is detected, at which time the transaction smart contract disposes of the digital property. Embodiments further include causing the transaction smart contract to be funded with the digital property, and determining that the triggering event has occurred. The transaction smart contract is then triggered to dispose of the digital property based on the triggering event.

column12: ALARMSYSTEM FÜR PERSÖNLICHES EIGENTUM
column13: The present invention relates to a personal property alarm system for monitoring the security of personal property using two-way coded radio signalling. The system comprises an alarm unit to be fixed to an item of property to be protected and a personal unit to be carried by a property owner. The alarm unit and the personal unit each comprise a transceiver to transmit and receive signals between each other. The alarm unit also comprises a motion sensor that is activated by predetermined movement of the property. The personal unit is operable in an alarm mode in which an alarm is activated to alert the property owner. The alarm unit is normally operable in a standby mode and is switched from the standby mode to an emergency mode when the motion sensor is activated. The personal unit alarm mode is activated when its transceiver receives an emergency signal from the alarm unit or when no standby signal has been received from the alarm unit. A personal unit may be tuned to communicate with a plurality of alarm units and/or a plurality of other personal units.

column12: METHOD OF SEPARATING AN EXPOSED THERMAL TRANSFER ASSEMBLAGE
column13: In a method of using a donor element in a radiation-induced thermal transfer process, an assemblage is provided that includes a donor element and a receiver element, wherein the donor element has a support layer and a transfer layer having one side adjacent the support layer and the other side adjacent the receiver element. After image-wise exposing the assemblage to radiation whereby a portion of the transfer layer is transferred to the receiver element, relative movement between the support layer and the receiver element is provided before separating the donor element from the receiver element. Advantages include improved edge straightness, image width predictability, improved thermal mass transfer, and improved color filters.

column12: Systems and methods for generating smart contracts to manage escrow transactions
column13: A method comprising: receiving information about an escrow transaction involving first and second parties, the first party providing a digital property and the transaction including at least one term required to be met for the property to be distributed to the other party 400; generates a transaction smart contract based on the information, wherein the smart contract holds the digital property and disposes of the property based on a triggering event 401; causes the contract to be funded wherein funding includes providing the property to the contract for holding 402; determines that the triggering event has occurred 403 and triggers the contract to dispose of the property based on the event 404. The triggering event may be: full or partial performance by the second party of the term to be met, failure of performance by the second party of the term, expiration of a timer, a contesting of the escrow transaction and/or an explicit trigger of the contract. Disposing of the property may include, returning a portion (of the property) to the first party, distributing a portion to the second party and/or forwarding a portion to a mediator. Also disclosed are a system and computer-based tool for implementing the method.

column12: Fastener tool loading assembly
column13: An assembly for loading a tool for driving uncollated nails. The tool includes a body with a driver blade for driving fasteners supplied from a magazine carried by the body and supporting a row of nails. A pusher urges the nails along a feed path in the magazine. Individual nails are advanced from the magazine to a drive position in the drive track by an escapement mechanism, and an advanced nail is held in the drive position by a magnet assembly. The tool magazine is quickly and conveniently loaded with nails supplied in an oriented condition from a loading chute. The loading operation is automatic in response to engagement of the magazine with the chute, and does not require awkward manipulation of the pusher. Coupling members on the magazine and on the chute are mated by means of ramp and guide structures. In the mated position, stops in the nail path are opened to permit nails to slide from the chute into the magazine.

column12: Mixing chamber for gaseous fuel burner
column13: A gaseous fuel mixture burner has a mixing chambers from which the fuel mixture is fed to the burner 1, the mixing chamber being otherwise closed to the atmosphere and having an inlet pipe 9 for the admission of gaseous fuel to the chamber end an inlet pipe 10 for the admission to the chamber of primary air under pressure from a fan 10b. The fan is started when fuel control tap 9a is turned to a first position after which movement of the top to the "on" position allows gaseous fuel to enter the mixing chamber. A pressure detector 10c ensures that there is air pressure, if not it prevents operation of the fuel control tap. Details of a mixing chamber in a cooker are disclosed with air from a plenum chamber at the rear of the cooker also being used to cool the oven door. <IMAGE>

column12: A COLONIC OVERTUBE
column13: A colonic overtube (1) for maintaining a sigmoid colon in a straightened configuration has a proximal end for location externally of a colon, and a distal end (3) for insertion into a colon. A colonoscope lumen (4) extends through the overtube (1) to facilitate passing the overtube (1) over a colonoscope. The overtube (1) has a convoluted corrugation (5) which extends along the entire length of the overtube (1) from the proximal end to the distal end (3). The corrugated configuration of the overtube (1) provides the overtube (1) with laterally flexibility so that the overtube (1) may flex substantially without kinking during advancement of the overtube (1) through a colon. A flexible seal, in the form of a tubular silicone sheath (6) of film material, is provided at the distal end (3) of the overtube (1) for sealing between the overtube (1) and a colonoscope extending through the colonoscope lumen (4). The flexible nature of the seal (6) enables the seal (6) to adapt itself to the size of the colonoscope extending through the colonoscope lumen (4) to achieve a secure, effective seal between the overtube (1) and a colonoscope regardless of the colonoscope size.

The corrugated configuration of the overtube 1  provides the overtube 1  with laterally flexibility so that the overtube 1  may flex substantially without kinking during advancement of the overtube 1  through a colon. A flexible seal, in the form of a tubular silicone sheath 6  of film material, is provided at the distal end 3  of the overtube 1  for sealing between the overtube 1  and a colonoscope extending through the colonoscope lumen 4.  The flexible nature of the seal 6  enables the seal 6  to adapt itself to the size of the colonoscope extending through the colonoscope lumen 4  to achieve a secure, effective seal between the overtube 1  and a colonoscope regardless of the colonoscope size.

column12: HIGH CAPACITY DENSITY LAMINATION / DECOUPLING CAPACITOR STRUCTURE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a cheap capacitor structure capable of reducing a leakage current of a capacitor and a capability of an electric short circuit between the capacitor and a plate.

SOLUTION: There is provided a capacitor structure 10 including a semiconductor base region 30 having a top face, a wale 12 which is formed adjacent to the top face in the semiconductor base region 30, a primary dielectric layer 38 adjacent to at least one part of the top face, and a polysilicon layer 16 adjacent to the primary dielectric layer 38. The wale 12, the primary dielectric layer 38 and the primary polysilicon layer 16 form a primary capacitor, and are aligned along a flat area. This capacitor structure 10 further includes: a primary conductive layer 201, at least one part of which being provided so as to be overlapped on at least one part of the polysilicon layer 16; a secondary dielectric layer 202adjacent to the primary conductive layer 201; and a secondary conductive layer 203adjacent to the secondary dielectric layer 202. The primary conductive layer 201, the secondary dielectric layer 202and the secondary conductive layer 203form a secondary capacitor, and are aligned along the flat area.

column12: Shock absorbing materials
column13: 1,071,152. Laminates. MINISTER OF AVIATION and BTR INDUSTRIES Ltd. Nov. 15, 1963 [Nov. 16, 1962], No. 43510/62. Heading B5N. A shock absorbing material comprises a plurality of superimposed flexible fibrous sheets coated or impregnated with a polymeric material as defined below, adjacent sheets being adhesively secured together at intervals along parallel areas of contact and separated from one another between these areas to provide a series of holes or elongated spaces having parallel axes between adjacent sheets. The polymeric material used comprises plasticized P.V.C., polythene, flexible epoxy or polyurethane resins, polyacrylic resins, or a flexible polyester, prepared, from a solution in a cross-linking agent such as styrene, of the rection product of a glycol, a dibasic aliphatic acid of more than 4 C atoms, and an a, #, unsaturated acid. In one method of making the material a sheet of polyethylene glycol terephthalate is laid over a row of rods 15 on a base-plate 10, the row comprising alternately rods of hexagonal cross-section and rods of semi-hexagonal crosssection. A layer of glass cloth 16 impregnated with the polyester resin used is laid on the surface of the rods and a row 17 of rods of hexagonal cross-section placed on the cloth to fill the troughs formed by the first row. Successive cloth layers and rods are then applied until the desired thickness is reached; a sheet of polyethylene terephthalate is placed on top of the assembly and a top-plate 12 tightened by wing nuts 13. The assembly is left for an hour to get the resin and then heated to cure the resin, and the rods, which may be coated with wax or other released agent, are removed. In an alternative method fabric honeycomb is expanded, impregnated with the resin, and set. Examples of fibrous materials used are woven or non-woven glass fibres, polyester fibres such as polyethylene terephthalate, rayon or acrylic fibres. A flexible epoxy resin usable comprises a mixture of epoxy resin, liquid polysulphide rubber (50 : 50) and triethylene tetramine.

column13: 1,144,055. Valves. DOWTY HYDRAULIC UNITS Ltd. 7 July, 1966 [4 June, 1965], No. 23972/65. Heading F2V. [Also in Division G3] A spool valve 15 is biased to the neutral position shown by a spring 27 and in this position connects an inlet (29) to an exhaust port 40 via chamber (30) of a similar parallel spool valve (16), check valve (37) and chamber 41. When spool 15 is moved to the left by lever 17, land 25 stops communication between chamber 41 and port 40 and connects passage 39, which also communicates with the inlet, with chamber 48 leading to one side of a jack 51. Fluid from the other side of the jack is expelled to exhaust port 40 via line 68, check valve 67 (which is opened by cam 65 on the spool), chamber 51 and passage 45. Rightward movement of the spool from the neutral position connects the left-hand side of the jack to passage 39 via chamber 51 and check valve 67 and connects the right-hand side of the jack to exhaust via chamber 48 and passage 46. Each spool 15, 16 has a separate operating lever 17 and grooves 53, 54 which co-operate with a respective spring-pressed detent ball 61 to hold the spool in its work positions. Radial passages 72, 73 in the lands 24, 25 communicate with axial passage 70 in the spool, the end of the latter normally being closed by a relief valve 71. If, when the spool is in one of its work positions, the pressure supplied to the jack exceeds a predetermined value, then the relief valve is unseated and allows fluid pressure to act on one or the other of the seats for spring 27 to cause the spool to be returned to its neutral position. The spool may be replaced by a valve of rectangular cross-section having an elongated slot which at all times is open to a pressure supply port, this slot being capable of connecting the supply to either of the work ports whilst the end edge portions of the valve control exhaust of fluid from the unpressurized work port. The detent means may be withdrawable from the indents automatically under fluid pressure when the pressure in the work ports exceeds a predetermined value.

column12: Composición termoplástica

column12: Thermoplastische Zusammensetzung
column13: Die vorliegende Erfindung betrifft eine thermoplastische Zusammensetzung insbesondere für den Einsatz in der Extrusion und Compoundierung, umfassend eine kontinuierliche Phase, die wenigstens ein erstes Polymer aufweist, welches aus einer Gruppe ausgewählt wird, welche einen Polyester, ein Polyesteramid, ein Polyesteretheramid, ein aliphatisches oder teilaromatisches Polyesterurethan oder Abmischungen davon, insbesondere solche Verbindungen oder Abmischungen mit hydrophoben Oberflächeneigenschaften aufweist und wenigstens eine dispergierte Phase, die als zweites Polymer wenigstens einen biogenen Vernetzer umfasst, welcher einen Wasseranteil von 0,1 bis 30 Gew. %, insbesondere von 5 bis 25 Gew. % in Bezug auf dessen Gesamtgewicht aufweist und worin das erste Polymer der kontinuierlichen Phase nicht mit dem zweiten Polymer der dispergierten Phase mischbar ist, und wenigstens einen anorganischen Füllstoff, und wenigstens einen Weichmacher aufweist. Die erfindungsgemäße Zusammensetzung ist dadurch gekennzeichnet, dass sie den Weichmacher Diglycerin oder Abmischungen mit Diglycerin aufweist und der Füllstoff einen Anteil von 0,1 bis 40 Gew. % in Bezug auf das Gesamtgewicht der Zusammensetzung hat.

column12: High capacitive density stacked decoupling capacitor structure
column13: A capacitive structure (10). The capacitive structure comprises a semiconductor base region (30) having an upper surface, a well (12) formed within the semiconductor base region and adjacent the upper surface, a first dielectric layer (38) adjacent at least a portion of the upper surface, and a polysilicon layer (16) adjacent the first dielectric layer. The well, the first dielectric layer, and the first polysilicon layer form a first capacitor and are aligned along a planar dimension. The capacitive structure further comprises a first conductive layer (201) positioned with at least a portion overlying at least a portion of the polysilicon layer, a second dielectric layer (202) adjacent the first conductive layer, and a second conductive layer (203) adjacent the second dielectric layer. The first conductive layer, the second dielectric layer form a second capacitor and are aligned along the planar dimension.

column12: Fastener driving tool
column13: A tool for driving uncollated nails includes a tool body with a nose portion defining a drive track wherein a driver blade moves in drive and return strokes. A magazine carried by the body supports a row of nails, and a pusher urges the nails along a feed path toward the drive track. The magazine is adjustable for tailoring the feed path width to the nail size. Individual nails are advanced from the magazine to a drive position in the drive track by an escapement mechanism operated in timed relationship with the driver blade, and an advanced nail is held in the drive position by a magnet assembly supported by the tool nose portion. Nails are positively advanced and are properly oriented by the escapement mechanism independently of the number of nails, the pusher force, or other conditions in the magazine. The tool magazine is quickly and conveniently loaded with nails supplied in an oriented condition from a loading chute. The loading operation is automatic in response to engagement of the magazine with the chute, and does not require awkward manipulation of the pusher. Coupling members on the magazine and on the chute are mated by means of ramp and guide structures. In the mated position, stops in the nail path are opened to permit nails to slide from the chute into the magazine.

column12: TREATMENT OF BONY DEFECTS WITH OSTEOBLAST PRECURSOR CELLS
column13: Healing of bony defects is promoted by suspending osteoblast precursor cells (OPCs) in a porous matrix, which is implanted in the bony defects. The OPCs may be transformed to express a bone morphogenetic protein (BMP), such as BMP-2. Devices are also disclosed for introducing the OPCs into bony defects. One device is a cannula (100) having concentric passageways, such that an endoscope (122) can be introduced through one of the passageways, while the OPCs are introduced through the endoscope or through another passageway without increasing pressure on the OPCs to such an extent that the cells are damaged. A cartridge unit (126) can be inserted through an endoscope to gently advance a cellular suspension through a catheter into the bone.

column12: Removing resin from metallic surfaces
column13: An organic resinous coating is removed from a metallic surface by treating the surface first with a stripping composition containing a phenol and/or a chlorinated hydrocarbon, and then with a solution of chromic acid. Examples of phenols and chlorinated hydrocarbons are, respectively, phenol, cresol and xylenol; and monochlor-, dichlor-, and trichlor-benzene, trichlortoluene, methylene chloride, ethylene dichloride, methyl chloroform, dichlorethylene, trichlorethylene and p perchlorethylene. The stripping composition may also contain a detergent emulsifier, e.g. an alkali metal (including ammonium), amine or alkanolamine salt of an organic acid, such as potassium oleate, or a non-ionic condensation product of ethylene oxide with aromatic materials and fatty alcohols, and an inhibitor, e.g. sodium phosphate and sodium chromate, and is preferably used as an aqueous solution. The chromic acid solution is preferably of 5-15% w/v strength, and may also contain an inhibitor such as barium and/or silver chromate. Between the treatments with the stripping composition and the chromic acid solution, the surface may be treated in an alkali solution, e.g. one containing an alkali metal silicate such as sodium metasilicate, an alkali metal carbonate, an alkali metal phosphate, an alkali hydroxide, or an aluminate. If necessary, the surface may again be treated in the alkali solution after treatment with the chromic acid solution, and then be treated again in the chromic acid solution. Metallic surfaces composed of aluminium alloys, magnesium alloys, steels and cadmium-plated steels, may be treated. Coatings formed of phenolic resin are referred to.

column12: Method of separating an exposed thermal transfer assemblage
column13: In a method of using a donor element in a radiation-induced thermal transfer process, an assemblage is provided that includes a donor element and a receiver element, wherein the donor element has a support layer and a transfer layer having one side adjacent the support layer and the other side adjacent the receiver element. After image-wise exposing the assemblage to radiation whereby a portion of the transfer layer is transferred to the receiver element, relative movement between the support layer and the receiver element is provided before separating the donor element from the receiver element. Advantages include improved edge straightness, image width predictability, improved thermal mass transfer, and improved color filters.

column12: Intelligent field interface device for fluid storage facility
column13: An intelligent field interface device for use in a fluid storage facility is disclosed. A bidirectional standard serial communication bus (20) provides communication between a plurality of the interface devices (17) and a central location (18). Surge and lightning protection (50, 51) as well as a high degree of electrical and magnetic isolation (45) are provided between the power supplies of the system. Each device includes a local one chip microcomputer (35) which has a field set address (56) and communicates through optoisolation (27) with the bus through a UART (28). Analog multiplexing (40) of RTD outputs (176-179) or outputs of other transducers (162) is provided to a local to analog to digital converter (36) so that all measured tank parameters may be transmitted digitally back to the control location. An arrangement for both testing and operating a motor operated valve (110) through a two-wire circuit (141, 132) including a limit switch (119) is also shown.

column12: Wafer centering in pocket to improve azimuthal thickness uniformity at wafer edge
column13: The invention relates to wafer centering in pocket to improve azimuthal thickness uniformity at wafer edge. A method for reducing slippage of a wafer during film deposition includes pumping out a processing chamber while the wafer is supported on lift pins or a carrier ring and lowering the wafer onto support members configured to minimize wafer slippage during deposition of the film. A multi-station processing chamber, such as a processing chamber for atomic layer deposition, can include a chuck-less pedestal at each station having wafer supports configured to prevent the wafer from moving off center by more than 400 microns. To minimize a gas cushion beneath the wafer, the wafer supports can provide a gap of at least 2 mils between the back side of the wafer and the wafer-facing surface of the pedestal.

column12: SOPORTE PARA MEDIOS DE ILUMINACION.
column13: LA INVENCION SE REFIERE A UN ZOCALO (30) PARA UN ELEMENTO DE LUZ ASI COMO A UN PROCESO PARA LA FIJACION Y EL CONEXIONADO DE AL MENOS UN ELEMENTO DE LUZ CON AL MENOS UN ZOCALO. LA BASE DE LA INVENCION ES EL OBJETIVO DE CREAR UN ZOCALO (10-13) QUE PUEDA FABRICARSE CON BAJO COSTO, EL CLIENTE PUEDA MONTARLO SIN GRAN ESFUERZO Y QUE PUEDA COMPENSAR LAS IMPRECISIONES DE FABRICACION EN EL EXTREMO DE UN ELEMENTO DE LUZ. LA INVENCION RESUELVE ESTE PROBLEMA TECNICO AL PRESENTAR EL ZOCALO (10-13) AL MENOS UNA TAPA (20-23) PARA LA RECEPCION DE UNA PIEZA PREDETERMINADA DEL ELEMENTO DE LUZ (30) QUE PRESENTA UN CONTACTO DE CONEXION (70), ESTANDO DIMENSIONADA LA TAPA (20-23) DE TAL FORMA QUE PUEDE POSICIONARSE EL ELEMENTO DE LUZ (30). ADICIONALMENTE EL ZOCALO (10-13) PRESENTA AL MENOS UNA CAMARA (50) QUE ATRAVIESA AL MENOS PARCIALMENTE EL ZOCALO (30), PARA LA RECEPCION DE UN ELEMENTO DE CONTACTO (60), ESPECIALMENTE UNA CLAVIJA DE CONEXION. EL ELEMENTO DE CONTACTO (60) ESTA CONSTRUIDO DE TAL FORMA QUE INSERTADO FORMA UNA UNION CONDUCTORA DE LA ELECTRICIDAD POR PRESION CON EL CONTACTO DE CONEXION (70).

column12: PHENYLENE OXO-DIESTER PLASTICIZERS AND METHODS OF MAKING
column13: A process for making non-phthalate, 1,2-phenylene oxo-diester plasticizers for polymer compositions, by selectively hydrogenating naphthalene to form a partially hydrogenated naphthalene, oxygenating said partially hydrogenated naphthalene to form phenylene diacids, and esterifying said phenylene diacids with oxo-alcohols to form 1,2-phenylene oxo-diesters. Also a process for making phenylene oxo-diester plasticizers by selectively brominating xylenes to form bisbromomethylbenzene, catalytic carboalkoxylation of the bromo-compound to form phenylene diacetate, followed by transesterification to form the phenylene oxo-diester.

column12: Multiplexed arrangement for connecting a plurality of transducers to a field interface device at a storage tank
column13: A multiplexed circuit for selecting one of a plurality of vertically spaced resistance temperature devices (RTDs) in a fluid storage tank. An electronic multiplexer is used to select a particular one of a plurality of vertically spaced RTDs to be connected to circuitry for reading the output value of same. The device is used in connection with an intelligent field interface device (FID) at the tank. The FID contains a table storing values for expected ranges of output values from the RTDs. When a value actually read is out of range, the FID causes the multiplexer to select another RTD for reading. The arrangement also allows reading of temperatures at various levels within the tank, irrespective of the actual fluid level.

column12: WAFER CENTERING IN POCKET TO IMPROVE AZIMUTHAL THICKNESS UNIFORMITY AT WAFER EDGE
column13: The present invention provides a method to reduce slippage of a wafer during film deposition, comprising: a step of pumping out a processing chamber while a wafer is supported on lift pins or a carrier ring; and a step of lowering the wafer on supporting members formed to minimize wafer slippage during film deposition. A multi-station processing chamber, such as a processing chamber for atomic layer deposition (ALD), includes a chuck-less pedestal in each station including wafer support parts formed to prevent the wafer from moving in a state out of a center as much as more than 400 m. Moreover, to minimize gas cushion under the wafer, the wafer support parts provide a gap of at least 2 mil between a rear surface of the wafer and a wafer-facing surface of the pedestal.

column12: Driver-adjustable sensor apparatus, system, & method for improving traffic safety
column13: The present invention discloses methods, apparatuses, and a system for improving intervehicular traffic safety by facilitating driver awareness of nearby vehicular traffic activity. Methods are disclosed for monitoring, detecting, and tracking “adjacent vehicles” (AVs) and “adjacent vehicle movements” (AVMs); calculating and displaying AV/AVM status data; and recommending and/or executing intervehicular maneuvering actions as needed. A driver-adjustable sensor apparatus is disclosed, allowing driver adjustment of AV/AVM “detection perimeters” (to increase/decrease detection ranges) based on traffic conditions, driver preferences, triggering of legal or preset thresholds, etc. Multiple versions of a “driver-adjustable” sensor and display system monitor, detect, and track traffic adjacent to a reference vehicle; calculate and display AV/AVM status data; and recommend and/or execute routine or emergency maneuvering actions needed to maintain vehicle safety during congestion or other intervehicular events. Better driver awareness and improved traffic safety are the result. The invention is factory-installed or purchased as an aftermarket product.

column12: METHOD OF SEPARATING AN EXPOSED THERMAL TRANSFER ASSEMBLAGE
column13: In a method of using a donor element in a radiation-induced thermal transfer process, an assemblage is provided that includes a donor element and a receiver element, wherein the donor element has a support layer and a transfer layer having one side adjacent the support layer and the other side adjacent the receiver element. After image-wise exposing the assemblage to radiation whereby a portion of the transfer layer is transferred to the receiver element, relative movement between the support layer and the receiver element is provided before separating the donor element from the receiver element. Advantages include improved edge straightness, image width predictability, improved thermal mass transfer, and improved color filters.

column12: Apparatus for operating a motor driven device and testing state of series limit switch over same two-wire circuit
column13: Apparatus for operating a motor driven device and testing the state of a limit switch in series with the motor, in the environment of a field interface device in a tank farm is disclosed. During operation of a relatively high power relay (115), a latched (145) signal ties one side (130) of the two-wire circuit to ground through a low impedance (139). When testing of the state of a series limit switch (119) is needed, the same supply voltage is switched onto one side of the two-wire circuit (147) but the low side of the two-wire circuit is grounded through a relatively high impedance (135, 136) to prevent sufficient current for operating the relay coil (117) from flowing. The presence or absence of current through the high impedance is detected through a coupling device (137) which provides a logical one or zero on an output line (68) to determine whether the limit switch is open or closed.

column12: PROTECTING GROUPS IN POLYMERS, PHOTORESISTS AND PROCESSES FOR MICROLITHOGRAPHY
column13: The invention relates to a photoresist composition having a protecting group and a protected material incorporated in a cyclic chemical structure. In this invention a protected material has a cyclic ether group or cyclic ester group as a protecting group. A specific example of a cyclic ether group is an alkylene oxide, such as an oxetane group, substituted with one or more fluorinated alkyl groups. A specific example of a cyclic ester is a lactone which may be substituted with methyl groups. The photoresist composition further includes a photoactive component. The photoresist composition of this invention has a high transparency to ultraviolet radiation, particularly at short wavelengths such as (193) nm and (157) nm.

column12: Ristet kaffe og kafferistningsfremgangsmåde
column13: A two stage coffee roasting process includes a first stage, green coffee beans are roasted for 5-15 minutes to a roast color of 30-50 Lu. In a second stage, the beans are further roasted for 1/2 -31/2 minutes to a roast color of 4-19 Lu. The roasted beans have a reduced density in the range of 0.27-0.38, and a roast color of 4-19 Lu. Analysis of sulfur compounds in the coffee aroma reveals a high level of methylmercaptan, a key compound for the pleasant aroma of freshly roasted and ground coffee. column12: ROASTED COFFEE AND COFFEE ROASTING METHOD
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To obtain roasted coffee retaining the increase of extracted coffee amount of rapidly roasted coffee and having an increase in a package/head space/methylmercaptan content and to provide a method for roasting coffee. SOLUTION: This method for roasting coffee comprises (a) at a first stage, bringing raw coffee beans into contact with a heated roasting gas for 5-15 minutes until the raw coffee beans are roasted into 30-50 Lu roasting color, (b) at a second stage, bringing the coffee beans heated by the first stage into contact with a heated roasting gas for 0.3-3.5 minutes to give roasted coffee beans having 4-19 roasting color and (c) rapidly cooling the roasted coffee beans, stopping roasting to give roasted coffee having 0.27-0.38 density and 4-19 Lu roasting color.

column12: COMBINED HANDSET AND HEADSET ARRANGEMENT.
column13: Lorsque l'on combine un système de communication standard de bureau avec un distributeur automatique d'appel (ACD) il est préférable de concevoir le système pour qu'il accepte plusieurs modes de fonctionnement. Deux de ces modes sont: le fonctionnement par combiné téléphonique de main, où un usager d'une station parle et écoute à l'aide d'un instrument conventionnel tenu à la main (202), et un mode de fonctionnement par un combiné téléphonique de tête (23) où l'usager possède un écouteur et un embout supportés par la tête. Dans le mode de fonctionnement du combiné de tête, la station associée (S1) se trouve en permanence dans un état décroché et les appels qui arrivent sont signalés par un signal court de tonalité (19) suivi par une connection automatique à la partie appelée. Dans le mode de fonctionnement du combiné conventionnel (de main), des signaux d'appel doivent être appliqués à la station (S1), et ces signaux se poursuivent jusqu'à ce qu'un état ultérieur décroché de la station (S1) ait répondu à l'appel d'entrée. L'agencement décrit permet à chaque station (S1) de fonctionner soit dans un mode soit dans l'autre en fonction des appels.

column12: PROTECTING GROUPS IN POLYMERS, PHOTORESISTS AND PROCESSES FOR MICROLITHOGRAPHY
column13: The invention relates to a photoresist composition having a protecting group and a protected material incorporated in a cyclic chemical structure. In this invention a protected material has a cyclic ether group or cyclic ester group as a protecting group. A specific example of a cyclic ether group is an alkylene oxide, such as an oxetane group, substituted with one or more fluorinated alkyl groups. A specific example of a cyclic ester is a lactone which may be substituted with methyl groups. The photoresist composition further includes a photoactive component. The photoresist composition of this invention has a high transparency to ultraviolet radiation, particularly at short wavelengths such as (193) nm and (157) nm.

column12: COMBINED HANDSET AND HEADSET ARRANGEMENT
column13: When a standard business office communication system is combined with automatic call distributor (ACD) features, it is preferred to design the system to accomodate a variety of operational modes. Two such modes are: handset operation, where a station user talks and listens via conventional hand-held instrument (202), and headset (23) operation where the user has an earphone and mouthpiece supported by the head. In headset operation, the associated station (S1) is made to appear off-hook permanently and incoming calls are signaled by a short burst of audio tone (19) followed by an automatic connection to the called party. In handset operation, ringing signals must be applied to the station (S1), and these signals continue until the incoming call is answered by a subsequent off-hook condition of the station (S1). The disclosed arrangement allows each station (S1) to operate in either mode on a per call basis.

column12: Open-end rotor spinning station has a yarn take-off tube for the yarn to travel on a straight path and then transfer into a diverging path to the take-off rollers with splicing rollers at the robot/spinner with yarn deflection
column13: The yarn take-off tube, especially at an open-end rotor spinning station, leads the spun yarn (9) along an initial path (I) through the take-off tube (8) with little or no deflection. The yarn is transferred to a second path (II) at the outlet of the take-off tube, which takes it increasingly away from the line of the first path. The yarn take-off tube at an open-end spinner has a slit passage, with a decreasing length from the outlet to the inlet side. The passage has a circular cross section at the entry. The narrow side surfaces of the slit are rounded, and the long sides of the slit are parallel at least at the outlet. The yarn on the second path lies against the inner wall of the yarn take-off tube, at least at the outlet. The second yarn path is curved. The inner wall of the take-off tube is structured, at least along the second path, or it has a hard coating or an insert of a hard material at the outlet to form part of the tube inner surface. The coating or the insert are preferably of a ceramic material. The base body of the yarn take-off tube is of metal. The yarn take-off tube is extended by a take-off jet (7), which are bonded together or are in a one-piece structure. The cross section of the take-off tube can be restricted by a throttle at or near the tube outlet, using a swing plate. The mounting of the swing throttle section is vertically below the center of gravity with a horizontal offset. Or the throttle is a slide which is pushed into the take-off tube, with a spring to hold it in the open or closed position. The restricted passage, defined by the throttle, is a multiple of the spun yarn thickness and preferably three times the yarn cross section. The throttle can also be a groove or recess, to take the running yarn, and the throttle is laid at the yarn to reduce the passage cross section, using an elastic material for the throttle to apply a pliable pressure on the yarn. The throttle is of a wear-resistant material, where an opening is worn away by the running yarn. When the throttle is in place to close the yarn take-off tube, the second yarn path is free. The throttle assembly is fitted as a conversion kit, with a release clip or ratchet mounting at the yarn take-off tube. An Independent claim is included for an open-end spinning station with an operating unit to manipulate the throttle in the yarn-take-off tube. Preferred Features: The spinning station or a mobile robot (2) has a yarn transfer system (13,16) to carry the yarn from the first to the second path at the take-off tube. The yarn transfer has at least one pair of splicing rollers or a yarn deflection, where at least one of the splicing rollers (14,15) in the pair has a movement on a swing arm (17,18) at the spinning station. The yarn can be deflected by a guide roller. After the yarn has been transferred from the first to the second path, it is detached by a deflection roller or the splicing rollers and transferred to the yarn take-off rollers (10) at the spinning station. A further Independent claim is included for a yarn splicing operation where, at the start of the splicing action, the yarn travels along the first path as it is taken from the spinner, and then transferred to the second path, to be drawn along it at the nominal production speed. Preferred Features: The yarn is transferred to the second path when it has reached the nominal travel speed, and the transfer action starts when the spinner is accelerated from the splicing speed to the nominal speed. The timing of the yarn transfer from the first to the second path is dependent on the characteristics of the spinning machine and the characteristics of the yarn fibers, and especially according to the acceleration behavior of the yarn take-off and/or the shear strength of the spun yarn.

column12: Method for preparing tinted contact lens
column13: An improved method is disclosed of imparting a tint or color to a soft, hydrogel contact lens by uniformly dispersing a dye throughout the lens. The dye is composed of a water-soluble compound essentially free of ethylenic unsaturation. A homogeneous solution of the dye in a hydrophilic monomer is prepared, the solution is subjected to polymerization conditions to yield a hydrophilic polymer from which the lens is formed, and the dye dispersed within the polymer is bonded to the polymer by contact with aqueous base prior to final hydration. The finished lens does not require soaking in an aqueous solution of the dye to impart the desired tint or color to the lens. Additionally, the dye uniformly dispersed throughout the lens according to the improved method does not leach out of the lens or migrate within the lens.

column12: Machine-learning model-based analytic for monitoring wind farm power performance
column13: A method for controlling a wind turbine includes detecting a plurality of analytic outputs relating to power performance of the wind turbine from a plurality of different analytics. The method also includes analyzing the plurality of analytic outputs relating to power performance of the wind turbine. Further, the method includes generating at least one computer-based model of the power performance of the wind turbine using at least a portion of the analyzed plurality of analytic outputs. Moreover, the method includes training the computer-based model(s) of the power performance of the wind turbine using annotated analytic outputs relating to the power performance of the wind turbine. In addition, the method includes estimating a power magnitude of the wind turbine using the machine-learned computer-based model(s). As such, the method includes implementing a control action when the power magnitude of the wind turbine is outside of a selected range.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR PROCESSING OF IMAGE DATA
column13: An apparatus and method for processing image data operates in a high capacity mode or a high quality mode. In the former a single bit per pixel is created and processed along one of two identical processing paths (101, 101'). The processing paths involve compression, buffering and expansion for output to a writer interface (126, 126', 130). The processing path selected for pixels in each image frame is in accordance with the most available buffering memory. In the latter mode two bits per pixel, a more significant bit (MSB) and a less significant bit (LSB) are created and processed simultaneously along the two processing paths. The processing path for each is selected in accordance with the LSBs being processed by the processing path with the most available memory. As compression of the LSBs is not as efficient as that of the MSBs, the number of document pages stored in the compression buffers is maximized.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR PROCESSING OF IMAGE DATA.
column13: L'invention concerne un appareil et un procédé de traitement de données d'images qui fonctionne dans un mode à grande capacité ou dans un mode à qualité élevée. Dans le mode antérieur, un seul bit par pixel est créé et traité le long d'un des deux chemins de traitement identiques (101, 101'). Les chemins de traitement comprennent la compression, la mise en mémoire tampon et l'expansion pour sortir les données vers une interface d'unité d'écriture (126, 126', 130). Le chemin de traitement sélectionné pour des pixels dans chaque trame d'image corresppond à la mémoire tampon la plus disponible. Dans le dernier mode, deux bits par pixel, un bit plus important (MSB) et un bit moins important (LSB), sont créés et traités simultanément le long des deux chemins de traitement. Le chemin de traitement pour chacun est sélectionné conformément au bit le moins important, traité par le chemin de traitement avec la mémoire la plus disponible. Lorsque la compression du LSB n'est pas aussi efficace que celle du MSB, le nombre de pages de document stocké dans les organes tampon de compression est maximisé.

column12: DEVICES AND METHODS FOR REINFORCEMENT LEARNING VISUALIZATION USING IMMERSIVE ENVIRONMENTS
column13: Disclosed are systems, methods, and devices for generating a visualization of a deep reinforcement learning (DRL) process. State data is received, reflective of states of an environment explored by an DRL agent, each state corresponding to a time step. For each given state, saliency metrics are calculated by processing the state data, each metric measuring saliency of a feature at the time step corresponding to the given state. A graphical visualization is generated, having at least two dimensions in which: each feature of the environment is graphically represented along a first axis; and each time step is represented along a second axis; and a plurality of graphical markers representing corresponding saliency metrics, each graphical marker having a size commensurate with the magnitude of the particular saliency metric represented, and a location along the first and second axes corresponding to the feature and time step for the particular saliency metric.

column12: AUTOMATIC CHEMISTRY ANALYZER
column13: An automatic chemistry analyzer includes a flow cell (17) mounted so that flow (18) through the cell and tubing connected to the cell is visible from the front of the housing. The electrodes (21-26) to the cell are removably plugged into the cell from their rear. The probe (32) aspirating sample fluid into an injection cell (28) is simultaneously washed by diluent and the diluent mixes with the fluid sample. Waste fluid from the flow cell (17) is fed to a basin (34) which then feeds under gravity to a waste drain (51). A ratio pump (65) is formed by selected syringes (72-74) which are band driven to deliver accurately prerequisite volumes of reagents to the flow cell (17). The solution ground (93) to the system is on the fluid line adjacent the entrance to the flow cell of fluid (19) thereby minimizing electronic noise. Only two motive means are necessary, one to effect horizontal and rotational movement of the sample tray, and a second to effect vertical motion of a crane (31) mounted probe (32) operative between sample cups (33) and an injection cell (28).

column12: SYSTEM FOR IMPROVED BIODETECTION
column13: A substance identification system is configured to identify at least one detection target faster and with greater accuracy than is possible using prior substance identification systems and/or prior substance identification techniques. A chamber includes a pellet forming area having a predetermined geometry that is configured to maximize a ratio of a pellet surface area to a pellet volume. A magnet is positioned on one side of the chamber and configured to form a pellet of aggregated magnetic particles in the pellet forming area. A laser source is positioned on the same side of the chamber as the magnet and configured to illuminate the pellet, when the pellet is formed in the pellet forming area.

column12: System and method for placing components in an electronic circuit design
column13: The present disclosure relates to a system and method for modeling the placement of components in an electronic circuit design. Embodiments may include receiving, at one or more computing devices, an electronic circuit design at a graphical user interface (GUI) and a selection for a component to be placed within the electronic circuit design. Embodiments may also include detecting a change in the position of the selected component to determine when the selected component is moved into a zone of the electronic circuit design. Embodiments may further include determining a component footprint and one or more padstacks associated with the component footprint for the selected component based upon the position of the selected component within the zone of the electronic circuit design. Embodiments may also include rendering the component footprint and the padstacks on the selected component based upon, at least in part, the position of the selected component.

column12: AN INSERTION DEVICE FOR AN ENDOSCOPE
column13: A probe system comprises an inflatable guide device (10) and a colonoscope (2). The guide device (10) comprises a sleeve of pliable material inverted upon itself to form an evertable tube with an inflation part for connection to an inflation tube (11). A leading edge of the guide device (10) is releasably secured to the colonoscope (2) during insertion into a colon. After insertion the leading edge is released and the guide device (10) is inflated. The colonoscope (2) may then be advanced through the colon in a spaced relationship to the walls of the colon by an everting motion of the guide device (10).

column12: MACHINE-LEARNING MODEL-BASED ANALYTIC FOR MONITORING WIND FARM POWER PERFORMANCE
column13: A method for controlling a wind turbine includes detecting a plurality of analytic outputs relating to power performance of the wind turbine from a plurality of different analytics. The method also includes analyzing the plurality of analytic outputs relating to power performance of the wind turbine. Further, the method includes generating at least one computer-based model of the power performance of the wind turbine using at least a portion of the analyzed plurality of analytic outputs. Moreover, the method includes training the computer-based model(s) of the power performance of the wind turbine using annotated analytic outputs relating to the power performance of the wind turbine. In addition, the method includes estimating a power magnitude of the wind turbine using the machine-learned computer-based model(s). As such, the method includes implementing a control action when the power magnitude of the wind turbine is outside of a selected range.

column12: Applied force monitor for apparatus for forming products from sheet material.
column13: This relates to an applied force monitor which is associated with sheet material forming mechanisms so as to determine whether sheet material is being properly formed by the amount of force applied in the formation thereof. A typical force applying member would be a cam. Suitable strain gauges are associated with the force applying member with the strain gauges being coupled in a bridge having a voltage output which is indicative of the applied force and which is directed to a microcomputer into which suitable indicia is selectively fed and such indicia will include high and low forces which would be indicative of a fault. The microcomputer includes a memory in which the faults are stored and in addition to indicating when individual faults do occur, the memory, when excess faults are determined, will serve to shut down the associated machine. Data may be visually displayed or may be permanently recorded by way of a printer.

column12: APPLIED FORCE MONITOR FOR APPARATUS FOR FORMING PRODUCTSAPPLIED FORCE MONITOR FOR APPARATUS FOR FORMING PRODUCTS FROM SHEET MATERIAL FROM SHEET MATERIAL
column13: This relates to an applied force monitor which is associated with sheet material forming mechanisms so as to determine whether sheet material is being properly formed by the amount of force applied in the formation thereof. A typical force applying member would be a cam. Suitable strain gauges are associated with the force applying member with the strain gauges being coupled in a bridge having a voltage output which is indicative of the applied force and which is directed to a microcomputer into which suitable indicia is selectively fed and such indicia will include high and low forces which would be indicative of a fault. The microcomputer includes a memory in which the faults are stored and in addition to indicating when individual faults do occur, the memory, when excess faults are determined, will serve to shut down the associated machine. Data may be visually displayed or may be permanently recorded by way of a printer.

column12: MACHINE-LEARNING MODEL-BASED ANALYTIC FOR MONITORING WIND FARM POWER PERFORMANCE
column13: Disclosed is machine-learning model-based analytic for monitoring wind farm power performance. A method for controlling a wind turbine includes detecting a plurality of analytic outputs relating to power performance of the wind turbine from a plurality of different analytics. The method also includes analyzing the plurality of analytic outputs relating to power performance of the wind turbine. Further, the method includes generating at least one computer-based model of the power performance of the wind turbine using at least a portion of the analyzed plurality of analytic outputs. Moreover, the method includes training the computer-based model(s) of the power performance of the wind turbine using annotated analytic outputs relating to the power performance of the wind turbine. In addition,the method includes estimating a power magnitude of the wind turbine using the machine-learned computer-based model(s). As such, the method includes implementing a control action when the power magnitude of the wind turbine is outside of a selected range.
column15: EVANS SCOTT CHARLES;;SUBRAMANIAN ARUNVENKATARAMAN;;WISE GERALD BOWDEN;;RIPPLE JR FRANK WILLIAM;;LAFLECHE JOHN EDMUND

column12: DEVICES AND METHODS FOR REINFORCEMENT LEARNING VISUALIZATION USING IMMERSIVE ENVIRONMENTS
column13: Disclosed are systems, methods, and devices for generating a visualization of a deep reinforcement learning (DRL) process. State data is received, reflective of states of an environment explored by an DRL agent, each state corresponding to a time step. For each given state, saliency metrics are calculated by processing the state data, each metric measuring saliency of a feature at the time step corresponding to the given state. A graphical visualization is generated, having at least two dimensions in which: each feature of the environment is graphically represented along a first axis; and each time step is represented along a second axis; and a plurality of graphical markers representing corresponding saliency metrics, each graphical marker having a size commensurate with the magnitude of the particular saliency metric represented, and a location along the first and second axes corresponding to the feature and time step for the particular saliency metric.
column15: TAYLOR MATTHEW EDMUND;;KARTAL BILAL;;HERNANDEZ LEAL PABLO FRANCISCO;;DOUGLAS NATHAN;;YIM DIANNA;;MAURER FRANK

column12: Automatic chemistry analyzer.
column13: An automatic chemistry analyzer includes a flow cell (17) mounted so that flow (18) through the cell and tubing connected to the cell is visible from the front of the housing. The electrodes (21-26) to the cell are removably plugged into the cell from their rear. The probe (32) aspirating sample fluid into an injection cell (28) is simultaneously washed by diluent and the diluent mixes with the fluid sample. Waste fluid from the flow cell (17) is fed to a basin (34) which then feeds under gravity to a waste drain (51). A ratio pump (65) is formed by selected syringes (72-74) which are band driven to deliver accurately prerequisite volumes of reagents to the flow cell (17). The solution ground (93) to the system is on the fluid line adjacent the entrance to the flow cell of fluid (19) thereby minimizing electronic noise. Only two motive means are necessary, one to effect horizontal and rotational movement of the sample tray, and a second to effect vertical motion of a crane (31) mounted probe (32) operative between sample cups (33) and an injection cell (28).

column12: FLUORINATED POLYMERS HAVING POLYCYCLIC GROUPS WITH FUSED 4-MEMBERED HETEROCYCLIC RINGS, USEFUL AS PHOTORESISTS, AND PROCESSES FOR MICROLITHOGRAPHY
column13: This invention provides novel fluorine containing polymers which comprise at least one fluorinated olefin, at least one polycyclic ethylenically unsaturated monomer with a fused 4-membered carbocyclic ring and, optionally, other components. The polymers are useful for photoimaging compositions and, in particular, photoresist compositions (positive-working and/or negative-working) for imaging in the production of semiconductor devices. The polymers are especially useful in photoresist compositions having high UV transparency (particularly at short wavelengths, e.g., 157 nm) which are useful as base resins in resists and potentially in many other applications.
column15: FEIRING ANDREW E;;SCHADT FRANK L III;;PETROV VIACHESLAV ALEXANDROVIC;;SMART BRUCE EDMUND;;FARNHAM WILLIAM BROWN

column12: PHOTORESISTS, FLUOROPOLYMERS AND PROCESSES FOR 157 NM MICROLITHOGRAPHY
column13: The invention provides a polymer having (a) at least one repeat unit derived from an ethylenically unsaturated compound having at least one fluorine atom covalently attached to an ethylenically unsaturated carbon atom; and (b) at least one repeat unit derived from an ethylenically unsaturated cyclic compound of structure: (I) wherein n is 0, 1, or 2; and R1 to R4 are independently H; C1-C10 alkyl or alkoxy, optionally substituted by halogen or ether oxygens; or C6-C20 aryl. These polymers can be used in making photoresist compositions and coated substrates.
